procstep.procdesc:
The ArcEditor toolbar in ArcMap 9.0 was used to trace streamlines from 1:50000 maps of the study area. Digitization was done from upstream to downstream. Some lines, particularly those in the Mexican portion of Rio Hondo, were also acquired from El Colegio de la Frontera Sur (Chetumal, Mexico), copied, and merged with hand digitized lines. The flow direction was manually corrected for the Mexico lines.
The maps used were as follows. For Belize, maps were published by the Director of Military Survey (Ministry of Defense, United Kingdom), with field survey by the Directorate or Overseas Services (DOS). The following Belize sheets were used (sheet number, publication year, base photography date):
1 (1993, 1988); 2 (1993,1988); 3 (1993,1988); 4 (1976,1970); 5 (1993,1988); 6 (unknown); 7 (1990,1979); 8(1993,1988); 9 (1993,1988); 10 (1993,1988); 11 (1993,1988); 12 (1980,1970); 13 (1993,1988); 14 (1993,1988); 15 (1993,1988); 16 (1993,1988); 18 (1993,1988); 19 (1993,1988); 20 (1993,1988); 21 (1993,1988); 23 (1993,1988); 24 (1993,1988); 25 (1993,1988); 26-27 (1993,1988); 28 (1993,1988); 29 (1993,1988); 30 (1993,1988); 31 (1993,1988); 33 (1993, 1988); 34 (1993,1988); 35 (1993,1988); 36 (1993,1988); 37 (1993,1988); 38 (1993,1988); 39 (1993,1988); 40 (1980,1970); 41 (1993, 1988); 42 (1993,1988); 44 (1993,1988).
For Guatemala, maps were published by the Instituto Geografico Militar, Ministerio de la Defensa Nacional de Guatemala were used. The following Guatemalan sheets were used (sheet number, publication year, base photography date):
2363I (1989, 1987), 2363II (1990, 1987), 2363III (2001, 2001), 2363IV (1989, 1987), 2364I (1990, 1987), 2364II (1990, 1987), 2364III (1990, 1987), 2364IV (1990, 1987), 2365I (1976, 1954), 2365II (1977, 1962), 2365III (1990, 1987), 2365IV (1989, 1987), 2366I (1976, 1954), 2366II (1974, 1954), 2366III (1989, 1987), 2366IV (1992, 1987), 2367I (1973, 1954), 2367II (1973, 1954), 2367III (1992, 1987), 2367IV (1992, 1987), 2368I (1973, 1954), 2368II (1973, 1954), 2368III (1972, 1954), 2368IV (1973, 1954), 2369II (1973, 1954), 2369III (1973, 1954), 2463IV (1987, 1989).
For Mexico, maps published by the Instituto Nacional de Estadistica Geografia Informatica (INEGI) were used. The following sheets were used (sheet number, publication year, base photography date):
E16A53 (1987, ?), E16A54 (1987, ?), E16A55 (1987, ?), E16A56 (1987, ?), E16A62 (1988, ?), E16A63 (1987, ?), E16A64 (1987, ?), E16A65 (1987, ?), E16A66 (1987, ?), E16A72 (1987, ?), E16A73 (1987, ?), E16A74 (2001, ?), 16A75 (2001, ?), E16A82 (1987, ?), E16A83 (1987, ?), E16A84 (2001, ?), E16C12 (1988, ?), E16C13 (2001, ?), E16C14 (1987, ?)

dataLineage.statement:
This dataset contains vector streamlines for all of the domestic watersheds of Belize. The lines were hand digitized from 1:50,000 Ordinance Survey (DOS) maps from Belize that were scanned and georectified (Peter Esselman and Sandor Rickets, 2007). This dataset was modified Jan Meerman in 2013 providing each stream segment with attributes indicating stream order, elevation, slope and where available names. A minor update was performed in July 2013 to correct Rio Blanco and Smoky Branch in the Chiquibul portion of the Cayo District.
The stream order hierarchy was officially roposed in 1952 by Arthur Newell Strahler, a geoscience professor at Columbia University in New York City, in his article “Hypsometric (Area Altitude) Analysis of Erosional Topology.” When using stream order to classify a stream, the sizes range from a first order stream all the way to the largest, a 12th order stream. A first order stream is the smallest of the world's streams and consists of small tributaries. These are the streams that flow into and "feed" larger streams but do not normally have any water flowing into them. In addition, first and second order streams generally form on steep slopes and flow quickly until they slow down and meet the next order waterway. First through third order streams are also called headwater streams and constitute any waterways in the upper reaches of the watershed.
Going up in size and strength, streams that are classified as fourth through sixth order are medium streams while anything larger (up to 12th order) is considered a river. For example, to compare the relative size of these different streams, the Ohio River in the United States is an eighth order stream while the Mississippi River is a tenth order stream. The world’s largest river, the Amazon in South America, is considered a 12th order stream.
Given the fact that even the largerst rivers are barely above the "stream category" the maximum stream number assigned is "7".
Other than that, the Strahler system has been applied rather liberally. The second order stream for example has become a "grab-bag" category for your average small to medium sized stream.
Other attributes include: Name: Stream names as derived from the 1:50,000 Ordinace Survey (DOS) maps of Belize Slope: slope percentage derived from the original Esselman dataset Elevation: elevation in meters derived from the original Esselman dataset Notes: information about streams that go underground (many, but most not mapped), and streams over karstic limestone that will be subject to strong seasonality.
